## Performance Analysis

**(i) Data Structure:** Maintain spanning forest in RAM, buffered edges on disk with locality-aware partitioning, and periodic rebuild of compact connectivity structure.

**(ii) Amortized I/O:** O((n + mb)/B) per batch, where rebuild occurs every T/b batches.

**(iii) Query Time:** O(log_B n) average case, O(m/B) worst case when searching residual edges.

**(iv) Space:** O(n + m + T) where T is buffer threshold, typically Θ(n + m).

**(v) Optimizations:** 1) Adaptive rebuild threshold based on update/query ratio; 2) Multi-level buffering with hot/cold edge classification.

**(vi) Comparison:** Recomputing from scratch costs O((n+m)α(n,m)/B) per batch vs. O((n+mb)/B) amortized with batching—significant improvement when b << m.

## Why This Is Asked

This question blends sliding-window technique with binary search to analyze a threshold problem, testing practical algorithm design and reasoning about complexity.

## Key Concepts

- Sliding window for fixed-length subarray sums
- Binary search over the answer space
- Time/space trade-offs and edge-case handling
- Practical optimizations (early exit, optional prefix sums)

## Code Example

```javascript
function maxLWithSumAtMost(A, T) {
  const n = A.length;
  const ok = (L) => {
    let sum = 0;
    for (let i = 0; i < L; i++) sum += A[i];
    if (sum <= T) return true;
    for (let i = L; i < n; i++) {
      sum += A[i] - A[i - L];
      if (sum <= T) return true;
    }
    return false;
  };
  let lo = 1, hi = n, ans = 0;
  while (lo <= hi) {
    const mid = (lo + hi) >> 1;
    if (ok(mid)) { ans = mid; lo = mid + 1; } else { hi = mid - 1; }
  }
  return ans;
}
```

