## Why This Is Asked
This problem evaluates understanding of dynamic tree updates and amortized analysis, demonstrating the power of subtree aggregation over naive full recomputation.

## Key Concepts
- Tree DFS preprocessing for subtree computation
- Subtree size tracking for batch updates
- Lazy aggregation techniques
- Amortized cost analysis
- Performance trade-offs vs complete traversal

## Data Structure Details
- **Preprocessing**: O(n) DFS to compute subtree sizes and initial S
- **Per-edge update**: O(1) using δ × size[c] aggregation
- **Per-batch cost**: O(B) where B is batch size
- **Memory**: O(n) for storing subtree sizes and edge weights
- **Optimizations**: (1) Batch processing to reduce constant factors, (2) Cache-friendly array layout
- **Comparison**: DFS recomputation costs O(n) per batch vs O(B) with aggregation

## Code Example
```javascript
// Preprocessing
const adj = [...];
const n = adj.length;
const size = Array(n+1).fill(0);
const w = Array(n+1).fill(0); // w[c] = weight to parent
let S = 0;

function dfs(u, parent) {
    size[u] = 1;
    for (const v of adj[u]) {
        if (v !== parent) {
            dfs(v, u);
            size[u] += size[v];
            S += w[v] * size[v];
        }
    }
}

// Update function
function update(edge, newWeight) {
    const [p, c] = edge;
    const delta = newWeight - w[c];
    w[c] = newWeight;
    S += delta * size[c];
}
```

