## Why This Is Asked
This question tests the ability to design a practical data structure solution for maintaining top-K items under batch updates, balancing per-update cost and output cost, and comparing against naive approaches.

## Key Concepts
- **Top-K maintenance** with dynamic count updates
- **Batch amortization** — distributing work across batch items rather than per-event
- **Heap with lazy updates** — using a min-heap for efficient top-K tracking
- **Space-time trade-offs** — comparing near-linear space with output efficiency

## Code Example
```javascript
class TopKTracker {
  constructor(k) {
    this.k = k;
    this.counts = new Map();
    this.heap = new MinHeap(); // stores (count, id) pairs
  }

  processBatch(updates) {
    // Phase 1: Apply all deltas to hashmap
    for (const [id, delta] of updates) {
      const newCount = (this.counts.get(id) || 0) + delta;
      this.counts.set(id, newCount);
    }

    // Phase 2: Reconcile heap with updated counts
    for (const [id, delta] of updates) {
      const count = this.counts.get(id);
      if (this.heap.has(id)) {
        this.heap.update(id, count);
      } else if (this.heap.size < this.k) {
        this.heap.insert(id, count);
      } else if (count > this.heap.peekMin().count) {
        this.heap.replaceMin(id, count);
      }
    }
  }

  getTopK() {
    return this.heap.getAllSorted(); // returns K items sorted by count descending
  }
}
```

## Amortized Analysis
Each batch processes B events. Updating the hashmap costs O(B) total. Each heap operation costs O(log K), and at most B such operations occur per batch, yielding O(B log K) amortized time. Since B << N in practice (batch sizes are typically much smaller than total unique keys), this significantly outperforms re-scanning all N items after every batch, which costs O(N log N) per batch.

