## Code Example
```javascript
class ParityDSU {
  constructor(n) {
    this.parent = Array.from({ length: n }, (_, i) => i);
    this.parity = new Array(n).fill(0);
    this.rank = new Array(n).fill(0);
    this.isBipartite = true;
  }

  find(x) {
    if (this.parent[x] !== x) {
      const root = this.find(this.parent[x]);
      this.parity[x] ^= this.parity[this.parent[x]];
      this.parent[x] = root;
    }
    return this.parent[x];
  }

  union(x, y) {
    const rootX = this.find(x);
    const rootY = this.find(y);
    if (rootX === rootY) {
      if (this.parity[x] === this.parity[y]) {
        this.isBipartite = false;
      }
      return;
    }
    if (this.rank[rootX] < this.rank[rootY]) {
      this.parent[rootX] = rootY;
      this.parity[rootX] = this.parity[x] ^ this.parity[y] ^ 1;
    } else if (this.rank[rootX] > this.rank[rootY]) {
      this.parent[rootY] = rootX;
      this.parity[rootY] = this.parity[x] ^ this.parity[y] ^ 1;
    } else {
      this.parent[rootY] = rootX;
      this.rank[rootX]++;
      this.parity[rootY] = this.parity[x] ^ this.parity[y] ^ 1;
    }
  }

  processBatch(edges) {
    for (const [u, v] of edges) {
      this.union(u, v);
    }
    return this.isBipartite;
  }
}
```

## Comparison to Recomputing from Scratch
- **DSU with parity**: O(B α(n)) per batch, O(1) query
- **BFS/DFS recomputation**: O(n + m) per batch

The DSU approach provides a significant speedup when B << m, as it reuses information from previous batches rather than recomputing the entire graph structure.

