## Why This Is Asked
This question tests understanding of sliding-window quantile estimation with bounded memory—a practical problem in latency monitoring where old samples must fade out over time.

## Key Concepts
- Sliding window maintenance using a circular buffer
- Fixed-bin histogram design and bucket mapping
- Error bounds derived from bucket width

## Bucket Mapping
The value range [0, M) is divided into S equal-width buckets. A value x maps to bucket floor(x * S / M), giving each bucket a width of M/S.

## Choosing S
The number of buckets S trades off memory (O(S)) and accuracy. With bucket width M/S, the P95 estimate has error at most M/(2S). For 1% error, choose S ≈ 50*M. In practice, S = 100-1000 works well for typical latency ranges.

## Error Guarantees vs Exact Computation
- **Approximate P95**: The estimated percentile falls within the bucket containing the true P95. Maximum error is half the bucket width: M/(2S).
- **Exact P95**: Requires maintaining all W samples in the window and sorting them, which is O(W log W) per query.
- **Trade-off**: This histogram approach gives O(1) updates and O(S) queries with bounded error, vs O(1) updates and O(W log W) queries for exact computation.

## Code Example
```javascript
class SlidingWindowP95 {
  constructor(M, W, S) {
    this.M = M;
    this.W = W;
    this.S = S;
    this.buffer = new Int32Array(W);
    this.hist = new Int32Array(S);
    this.head = 0;
    this.count = 0;
  }

  add(x) {
    const b = Math.floor((x * this.S) / this.M);
    this.hist[b]++;

    if (this.count === this.W) {
      const y = this.buffer[this.head];
      const by = Math.floor((y * this.S) / this.M);
      this.hist[by]--;
    } else {
      this.count++;
    }

    this.buffer[this.head] = x;
    this.head = (this.head + 1) % this.W;
  }

  query() {
    const p95 = Math.floor(0.95 * this.count);
    let cum = 0;
    for (let b = 0; b < this.S; b++) {
      cum += this.hist[b];
      if (cum >= p95) return (b * this.M) / this.S;
    }
    return this.M;
  }
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you adapt this for non-uniform distributions or dynamic M?
- How does the choice of S affect query latency in a high-throughput system?

## Why This Question Is Asked
This question evaluates understanding of online quantile estimation using the P² algorithm, a space-efficient alternative to GK-style sketches. It tests practical knowledge of update mechanics, error behavior, and the trade-offs between approximation and exact computation in streaming contexts.

## Key Concepts
- The P² algorithm uses five fixed-position marker heights to approximate quantiles
- Piecewise-linear interpolation between markers yields quantile estimates
- Per-element updates are constant time with fixed memory overhead
- The algorithm provides guarantees that improve with larger sample sizes

## Code Example
```javascript
class P2Quantile {
  constructor(quantile = 0.5) {
    this.quantile = quantile;
    this.n = 0;
    this.markers = [0, 0, 0, 0, 0];
    this.positions = [0, 0.25, 0.5, 0.75, 1].map(p => p * 2);
  }

  update(value) {
    this.n++;
    if (this.n < 5) {
      this.markers[this.n - 1] = value;
      this.markers.sort((a, b) => a - b);
      return;
    }

    let j = this.quantile < 0.5 ? 1 : 3;
    if (value >= this.markers[j]) j++;

    for (let i = j; i < 5; i++) this.positions[i]++;

    for (let i = 1; i < 4; i++) {
      const d = this.positions[i] - this.positions[i-1];
      const target = (i + 1) * this.n / 4;
      if ((d > 1 && this.positions[i] < target) || 
          (d < 1 && this.positions[i] > target)) {
        const sign = d > 1 ? 1 : -1;
        this.markers[i] += sign * Math.min(d, Math.abs(this.positions[i] - target));
        this.positions[i] += sign;
      }
    }
  }

  getQuantile() {
    return this.markers[2];
  }
}
```

## Error Analysis
The P² algorithm exhibits decreasing error as more elements are processed. For uniform distributions, error is minimal; for skewed distributions, error may be slightly higher but remains bounded. Larger batch sizes reduce the frequency of updates but do not fundamentally alter the error characteristics.

## Comparison to Sorted Buffer
Maintaining a full sorted buffer of size N provides exact median computation but requires O(N) memory and O(log N) insertion time per element. The P² algorithm trades this exactness for constant memory and constant update time, making it suitable for memory-constrained streaming applications where approximate quantiles suffice.

