## Two Practical Optimizations
1. **Batch Coalescing**: Accumulate multiple batches in W before merging. This reduces merge frequency when B is small relative to h, yielding better amortized cost.
2. **Hull Caching**: Store precomputed angular ranges for each hull vertex to accelerate binary search queries, trading space for faster lookups.

## Performance Comparison: Incremental Merge vs. Rebuilding
| Approach | Per-Batch Cost | Query Time |
|----------|----------------|------------|
| Incremental merge | O(B + h) amortized | O(log h) |
| Full rebuild | O((n) log n) | O(log n) |

As n grows, incremental merging becomes increasingly advantageous since rebuilding re-sorts all n points each batch, while the incremental approach processes only O(B) new points plus O(h) for the affected hull region.

