## Code Example
```javascript
class Queue {
  constructor(capacity = B) {
    this.buffer = new Array(capacity);
    this.head = 0;
    this.tail = 0;
    this.size = 0;
  }

  enqueue(item) {
    if (this.size === this.buffer.length) {
      const newBuffer = new Array(this.buffer.length + B);
      for (let i = 0; i < this.size; i++) {
        newBuffer[i] = this.buffer[(this.head + i) % this.buffer.length];
      }
      this.buffer = newBuffer;
      this.head = 0;
      this.tail = this.size;
    }
    this.buffer[this.tail] = item;
    this.tail = (this.tail + 1) % this.buffer.length;
    this.size++;
  }

  dequeue() {
    if (this.size === 0) return undefined;
    const item = this.buffer[this.head];
    this.head = (this.head + 1) % this.buffer.length;
    this.size--;
    return item;
  }
}
```

## B's Influence
- **Total copies**: Larger B reduces growth frequency, cutting total copy work from O(N²) toward O(N) (since copies ≈ N²/(2B))
- **Cache behavior**: Smaller B keeps working set in cache but triggers more frequent expensive copies; larger B improves sequential access patterns during copies but may evict useful cache contents when reallocating

