## Code Example

```javascript
class DSU {
  constructor(n) {
    this.parent = Array.from({length: n}, (_, i) => i);
    this.size = new Array(n).fill(1);
    this.components = n;
  }

  find(a) {
    if (this.parent[a] !== a) {
      this.parent[a] = this.find(this.parent[a]);
    }
    return this.parent[a];
  }

  union(a, b) {
    const rootA = this.find(a);
    const rootB = this.find(b);
    if (rootA === rootB) return false;

    if (this.size[rootA] < this.size[rootB]) {
      [rootA, rootB] = [rootB, rootA];
    }
    this.parent[rootB] = rootA;
    this.size[rootA] += this.size[rootB];
    this.components--;
    return true;
  }
}

function processBatches(n, batches) {
  const dsu = new DSU(n);
  const results = [];

  for (const batch of batches) {
    for (const [u, v] of batch) {
      dsu.union(u, v);
    }
    results.push(dsu.components);
  }

  return results;
}
```

## Analysis

**Preprocessing:** O(n) time to initialize DSU arrays, O(n) memory for parent and size arrays.

**Per-batch updates:** O(B·α(n)) time for B union operations with path compression and union by size.

**Total complexity:** O(n + m·α(n)) time, O(n) memory.

**Comparison to recomputation:** Full DFS/BFS after each batch would cost O(n + m) per batch, totaling O((n + m)·(m/B)) time—significantly worse for large graphs with many small batches.

The DSU approach leverages amortized near-constant operations, making it ideal for dynamic connectivity scenarios with incremental updates.

